description.narrative: This Action aims to increase access to justice for vulnerable groups in Vietnam through a program of grant-making to civil society organizations (CSOs) linked to capacity development, networking, and evidence-based research for national-level policy dialogue. TheAction builds on the results of the Justice Initiatives Facilitation Fund#s first phase (2010-15) while incorporating lessons learnt and evaluation findings to design a focussed and targeted program that will achieve immediate outcomes and long-lasting impacts onincreasing access to justice for vulnerable groups. It will complement the PAGoDA component of JULE by ensuring that supply-side support for access to justice is met by demand from Vietnamese citizens, especially the most vulnerable. Oxfam particular added value as host of the Secretariat lies in our proven abilities to develop capacity of civil society partners, facilitate networks and multi-stakeholder platforms, and engage in innovative research and policy advocacy processes (among others, our eight-year longitudinal research on participatory poverty monitoring in Vietnam (2007-15), widely used by government and development partners in planning andprogram design), as well as management of the whole cycle of grant-making, monitoringand evaluation. Oxfam#s deep global experiencein human rights-based justice work makes us uniquely qualified to implement JIFF. Our in-house capacity # in Vietnam and at head office level # includes extensive research capacity, access to justice and legal aid, specialism in civil society capacity building and advocacy techniques, development of networks and multi stakeholder platforms, media and communications, and ICT.

participating-org.narrative: In Vietnam , Oxfam is one of the leading international, non -governmental organisation. Since 1955, Oxfam is active in Vietnam withhumanitarian interventions and started development work in the late 1980's. Today, Oxfam works in 26 provinces with people, governments and civil society to promote equality and well-being through social and economic change.
